ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.
M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Did you ever go on combat patrols or have other dangerous duty?
Notes: 1 = No; 2 = 1-3 times; 3 = 4-12 times; 4 = 13-50 times; 5 = 51 or more times

ElementDescription: Were you ever under enemy fire?
Notes: 1 = Never; 2 = less than 1 month; 3 = 1-3 months; 4 = 4-6 months; 5 = 7 or more months

ElementDescription: Were you ever surrounded by the enemy?
Notes: 1 = No; 2 = 1-2 times; 3 = 3-12 times; 4 = 13-25 times; 5 = 26 or more times

ElementDescription: What percentage of the soldiers in your unit were killed (KIA), wounded or missing in action (MIA)?
How often did you fire rounds at the enemy?
Notes: 1 = No; 2 = 1-2 times; 3 = 3-12 times; 4 = 13-50 times; 5 = 51 or more times

ElementDescription: How often did you see someone hit by incoming or outgoing rounds?
Notes: 1 = No; 2 = 1-2 times; 3 = 3-12 times; 4 = 13-50 times; 5 = 51 or more times

ElementDescription: How often were you in danger of being injured or killed (i.e., being pinned down, overrun, ambushed, near miss, etc.)?
Notes: 1 = No; 2 = 1-2 times; 3 = 3-12 times; 4 = 13-50 times; 5 = 51 or more times

ElementDescription: Combat Exposure Scale Total Score: Category
Notes: 1 = 0-8: light; 2 = 9-16: light to moderate; 3 = 17-24: moderate; 4 = 25-32: moderate to heavy; 5 = 33-41: heavy

ElementDescription: Approximately how many months have you served in combat deployments?
